{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:10:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:10:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11357"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11357"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.24,0.04,0.42,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4002"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46972"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4002"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31734"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8869"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42578"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46972"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62 year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of left eye redness and pain. On further history, he reports that the pain is felt behind the eye and is associated with some mild blurring of vision, as well as photophobia . He denies nausea, vomiting and headache. His medical history includes Crohn\u0027s disease, hypertension and osteoarthritis. On examination, he appears to be mildly uncomfortable with vital signs within normal limits. Corrected visual acuity is 6/18 in the left eye and 6/12 in the right eye. His left eye appears markedly reddened compared to the right side (Image). Pupillary reflexes are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Considering the most likely diagnosis, which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV acetazolamide and emergency ophthalmology consult","Topical chloramphenicol eye drops and review in one week","Topical lubricating eye drops and routine follow-up in one month","Urgent ophthalmology outpatient review","Topical timolol eye drops and routine follow-up in one month"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent ophthalmology oupatient review \u003C/strong\u003Efor consideration of topical steroid eye drops.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a progressive one-week history of left eye redness and pain, on a background of known Crohn\u0027s disease. These features of the history, as well as the symptoms of visual blurriness and retro-orbital pain, are characteristic of anterior uveitis. On examination, the reduced visual acuity and conjunctival injection with ciliary flush, further support this diagnosis. Treatment for this condition is steroid eye drops, however these should be only commenced by an ophthalmologist, or in consultation with one. The reason for this is that infections like herpes keratitis need to be excluded, as the use of steroid eye drops in the presence of such an infection can lead to sight-threatening complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV acetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment for acute angle closure glaucoma. This medication reduces the production of aqueous humour, and therefore, helps lowers intraocular pressure. Acute angle closure glaucoma is a worthwhile consideration in any patient who presents with a painful red eye, however the typical history of this condition is generally more dramatic and acute than the one described by this patient. Patients will often report nausea, vomiting and headache. On examination, the pupil will often be fixed and dilated, with corneal haziness a classical finding. These patient does not exhibit any of these findings, so IV acetazolamide is not the best answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical timolol eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E, are also used in the acute management of angle closure glaucoma. As a beta adrenergic blocker, timolol also reduces the intraocular pressure. As this patient does not appear to be suffering from an acute angle closure crisis, timolol is not indicated at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical chloramphenicol eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E are indicated in bacterial conjunctivitis. Patients suffering from bacterial conjunctivitis will often experience an irritating discomfort of the eye rather than overt pain. The pain itself is likely to be located anteriorly rather than posteriorly. On examination, conjunctival injection will be noted peripherally, often with sparing of the conjunctiva around the iris. A purulent discharge is sometimes observed. As this patient does not fit many of these symptoms and signs, topical chloramphenicol is not the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical lubricating eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E can bring about relief in viral and allergic conjunctivitis. Like with bacterial conjunctivitis, the history and exam findings in this particular case suggest a more serious cause. Whilst lubricating eye drops might assist as a comfort measure in cases of anterior uveitis, steroid eye drops are the mainstay of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Symptoms of visual blurriness and retro-orbital pain, in conjunction with examination findings of reduced visual acuity and conjunctival injection are characteristic of anterior uveitis."],"references":["Gilani CJ, Yang A, Yonkers M, Boysen-Osborn M. Differentiating urgent and emergent causes of acute red eye for the emergency physician. The Western Journal of Emergency Medicine. 2017;18(3):509\u201317. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5391903/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31734"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11357"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15279"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15279"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5dceeeee-eb40-41d2-84a4-50134bc175a3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5dceeeee-eb40-41d2-84a4-50134bc175a3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":640}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31734"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-14T13:37:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-09T17:44:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4002"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46972"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"r